<paragraph blockId="11.[151,684,170,535]" pageId="11" pageNumber="162">
<taxonomicName box="[177,415,171,197]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ehretiaceae" genus="Hilsenbergia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Boraginales" pageId="11" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="apetala">
<emphasis box="[177,415,171,197]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="162">Hilsenbergia apetala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a strikingly distinct species, easily recognized by its highly reduced corolla, which lacks lobes and has the staminal filaments adnate to it for its full length. It thus appears as though the staminal filaments are fused into a tube and no corolla is present. I am not aware of any other member of the 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Boraginales" pageId="11" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Ehretioideae">Ehretioideae</taxonomicName>
with this floral structure. It is also unusual in its nearly racemose inflorescence, which is usually reduced to a simple rachis, or occasionally has a few, highly-reduced lateral branches.
</paragraph>
